<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF206-968-054  </DOCNO><DOCID>06 968 054.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>MacWEEK  Jan 17 1989 v3 n3 p36(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT MacWEEK Inc. 1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Animation features added to Studio-1.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Guglielmo, Connie.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Electronic Arts (product introduction).andO;Product:   Studio-1 (Computer graphics software).andO;Topic:     Graphics SoftwareProduct IntroductionAnimationMonochromeScanning.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Animation features added to Studio/1andM;SAN MATEO, Calif.andP;  -- It may be monochrome, but it's not dull.andM;Electronic Arts has added some unusual features to Studio/1, its forthcomingblack-and-white paint program, including:andM;* Automatic facilities for creating simple animations.andP;  Multiframe animationscan then be saved as a &quot;paintbrush&quot; so users can easily create longeranimated sequences with a few brush strokes.andM;* A HyperCard Animation Driver that lets users incorporate Studio/1-generatedanimations directly into their stacks.andM;* Text layer for overlaying text on images.andP;  Instead of being treated as partof the bit-mapped image, text is output -- on a LaserWriter printer, forinstance -- as PostScript fonts.andM;* Direct support for the Apple Scanner so that images can be scanned fromwithin the program.andM;To be priced below $150 and scheduled for release in the second quarter,Studio/1 contains the same tool palette as Studio/8, the company's $495 colorpaint program.andM;Both programs will be demonstrated at the San Francisco Macworld Expo thisweek, along with Studio/24, a 24-bit color version now under development.andM;Electronic Arts is located at 1820 Gateway Drive, San Mateo, Calif.andP;  94404;(415) 570-5137.andO;</TEXT></DOC>